        "created_at": "2025-02-26T17:16:22.414Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Hi. I would like to find out my best way of moving my Signal account to a new phone after the previous one has become unavailable, while preserving history and other details as much as possible.</p>\n<p>Here is the story:</p>\n<p>I started using Signal on Android phone A, which is still available but not in regular use anymore. Almost immediately, I installled signal-desktop on my Linux PC and linked it to my account. Phone A basically works but has always had issues, so some time (more than a year) ago I transferred the Signal installation to Android phone B, using the function in the app. This way I recreated all settings and history on phone B. I’ve never tried to start Signal on phone A since then. The installed version on phone A is 6.28.6.</p>\n<p>In summer 2024, phone B became unusable (water damage) and won’t boot anymore. My signal-desktop installation has been my only access to Signal since then.</p>\n<p>I now would like to start using Signal on my new Android phone C, which works and has my original phone number. I would like to preserve as much information as possible (such as history and security keys, if that is the right term). I definitely want to keep my signal-desktop installation active and want my history and groups/contacts preserved there.</p>\n<p>I could still start Signal on phone A and rerun the transfer function if that helps, but I do not have a working SIM card for phone A anymore (as phone C has a different SIM format).</p>\n<p>Ideally I would like to use Molly one phone C rather than the official Signal app, but if that has to be done in a separate step I’m willing to start by installing the official app.</p>\n<p>What is my best (or indeed only) way to proceed? Thanks for any advice you can give me.</p>",
