        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/cuehd/{size}/42510_2.png",
        "created_at": "2025-02-26T19:34:16.717Z",
        "cooked": "<p><strong>Where your SIM is installed is irrelevant.</strong></p>\n<p>If you only need your history on the Linux PC, you can just install Signal or Molly on phone C. Set a Signal PIN on your Linux PC, then register phone C and use your Signal PIN to restore your contacts &amp; group memberships. You might need to relink your Linux PC after this, but you won’t lose anything on your PC during that process. Phone C will not have message history.</p>\n<p>If you want message history on phone C, you will need to do the above, create a backup from phone C, use <a href=\"https://github.com/bepaald/signalbackup-tools\">signalbackup-tools</a> to merge the empty phone C backup with the Linux PC database, delete your user data from phone C, then restore that merged backup onto phone C during the restore account process. You could also try this process using phone A (assuming you update it to the latest version), then make a full backup of phone A and transfer it to phone C or use the transfer function to move the history from phone A to phone C.</p>\n<p>For any of these processes you can leave the SIM in phone C and input the SMS that you receive there into whichever phone you are using. It also doesn’t matter if you use Molly or the official Signal client for this.</p>\n<p>edited to include the need to delete user data from the new phone.</p>",
